this is a good sliding-window / run-length style solution. I’ll walk you through the code step-by-step like you asked, explain what each variable means, show a concrete example, and finish with the time/space complexity and a small readability tip.

What this function does (plain English)

resultsArray examines every contiguous subarray (window) of length k in nums.
For each window it returns the last value of the window if the k numbers ending at that position form a strictly increasing sequence where each number is exactly +1 from the previous (i.e., consecutive integers). If the window does not contain such a consecutive run of length k, the result is -1 for that window.

Variables quick-reference

nums — input array of integers.

k — size of the sliding window.

n — size of nums.

result — vector to store answer for each window. Length = n - k + 1. Initialized with -1.

count — length of the current consecutive run (numbers that increase by exactly 1).

i — index for the result array (which window we’re writing).

j — right end index of the current window in nums.

Step-by-step walkthrough of the code
int n = nums.size();
vector<int> result(n-k+1, -1);


Compute n. Allocate result with one entry per window, initially -1.

int count = 1;


count will track how many consecutive +1 steps we have ending at the current index.

We start with 1 because a single number is a run of length 1 by itself.

Build the run length for the first window (indices 0 to k-1)
for(int i = 1; i < k; i++) {
    if (nums[i] == nums[i-1]+1) {
        count++;
    } else {
        count = 1;
    }
}


This loop walks from index 1 up to k-1 and measures the length of the consecutive sequence that ends at index k-1.

If every adjacent pair inside the first window differs by +1, count will become k.

If there is a break, count resets to 1 and the loop continues checking further pairs.

if (count == k) {
    result[0] = nums[k-1];
}


If the run that ends at k-1 is length k, that means the first window contains k consecutive increasing numbers, so we store the last value of the window (nums[k-1]) in result[0].

Slide the window across the array
int i = 1;
int j = k;

while (j < n) {
    if (nums[j] == nums[j-1] + 1) {
        count++;
    }else {
        count = 1;
    }

    if (count >= k) {
        result[i] = nums[j];
    }

    i++;
    j++;
}


j is the index of the new element entering the right side of the window.

We update count the same way: extend the consecutive run if nums[j] is exactly nums[j-1] + 1, otherwise reset to 1.

If count >= k, that means the last k elements ending at index j are consecutive (they form a run of length at least k), so the current window (which ends at j) should record nums[j].

Move both i (result index) and j (window right end) forward to process the next window.

At the end we return result.

Concrete example

Let nums = [2,3,4,1,2,3,4] and k = 3.
Number of windows = n - k + 1 = 7 - 3 + 1 = 5. Windows and expected outputs:

Window [2,3,4] (ends at index 2): consecutive → output 4.

Window [3,4,1] (ends at index 3): not consecutive → -1.

Window [4,1,2] (ends at index 4): not consecutive → -1.

Window [1,2,3] (ends at index 5): consecutive → 3.

Window [2,3,4] (ends at index 6): consecutive → 4.

Trace of count as j moves:

First loop builds count up to index k-1 = 2: comparisons (3==2+1) true → count=2, (4==3+1) true → count=3. So result[0] = 4.

j=3: 1 == 4+1? no → count=1 → result[1] stays -1.

j=4: 2 == 1+1? yes → count=2 → result[2] stays -1 (count < 3).

j=5: 3 == 2+1? yes → count=3 → result[3] = nums[5] = 3.

j=6: 4 == 3+1? yes → count=4 → result[4] = nums[6] = 4 (count>=k still valid).

Final result = [4, -1, -1, 3, 4].

Correctness note

count always represents the length of the consecutive run that ends at the current index. If count >= k, then the last k elements ending at that index are consecutive, which means the current window (ending at that index) satisfies the condition. So the logic is correct.

Complexity

Time: O(n) — every element is visited a constant number of times.

Extra Space: O(1) (ignoring the output result which is required and size n-k+1).

Small readability suggestion

Rename count to something clearer like runLen or consecLen.

The initial loop and the sliding loop share the same logic for updating count. You can keep them separately (as you did) or unify the logic to reduce repetition.

